LAYER 3: NOSE
the only sense wired directly to emotion

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the nose performs two functions: respiration and olfaction
olfaction is the only sense that does NOT relay through the thalamus before reaching the cortex
olfactory signals go directly from the olfactory bulb to the piriform cortex amygdala and entorhinal cortex
this is why smells trigger memories and emotions more powerfully than any other sense
the olfactory pathway is ancient phylogenetically predating vision and hearing

STRUCTURE external_nose | cartilage and bone framework covered by skin | nares nostrils open to the environment
STRUCTURE nasal_vestibule | anterior chamber | vibrissae nasal hairs filter large particles
STRUCTURE nasal_cavity | divided by the nasal septum into left and right chambers | lined by respiratory epithelium inferiorly and olfactory epithelium superiorly
STRUCTURE turbinates | conchae | three curved bony shelves on each lateral wall superior middle inferior | increase surface area for warming humidifying and filtering inspired air | turbulent airflow directs air superiorly toward olfactory epithelium
STRUCTURE paranasal_sinuses | air-filled cavities in frontal maxillary ethmoid and sphenoid bones | lighten the skull | produce mucus | resonance chambers for voice | lined by ciliated respiratory epithelium

OLFACTORY EPITHELIUM occupies approximately 5 cm² on the roof of the nasal cavity near the cribriform plate of the ethmoid bone

CELL_TYPE olfactory_sensory_neurons | OSNs | bipolar neurons | approximately 10-20 million in humans
    apical dendrite extends to the epithelial surface bearing 10-30 cilia immersed in mucus
    each OSN expresses ONE type of odorant receptor OR from a family of approximately 400 functional genes in humans
    this is the one receptor one neuron rule
    odorant receptors are G-protein coupled receptors GPCRs coupled to Gₒₗf
    when an odorant molecule binds the OR:
        Gₒₗf activates adenylyl cyclase III
        cAMP is produced
        cAMP-gated cation channels open on the cilia
        Na⁺ and Ca²⁺ flow in
        Ca²⁺ opens Ca²⁺-gated Cl⁻ channels
        Cl⁻ flows OUT of the neuron because intracellular Cl⁻ concentration is high in OSNs
        this Cl⁻ efflux further depolarizes the cell amplifying the signal
        the OSN fires action potentials
    axons of OSNs are among the thinnest unmyelinated axons in the body
    they pass through the cribriform plate of the ethmoid bone as olfactory fila CN I
    OSNs are one of the few neuron types that undergo continuous neurogenesis throughout life
    they are replaced every 30-60 days from basal stem cells in the olfactory epithelium

CELL_TYPE sustentacular_cells | supporting cells | provide metabolic and structural support | detoxify odorants via cytochrome P450 enzymes
CELL_TYPE basal_cells | stem cells | globose basal cells actively divide to replace OSNs | horizontal basal cells are quiescent reserve stem cells
CELL_TYPE Bowman's_glands | produce the mucus that covers the olfactory epithelium | odorants must dissolve in this mucus to reach the odorant receptors | odorant-binding proteins OBPs in the mucus help shuttle hydrophobic odorants to receptors

OLFACTORY BULB sits on the cribriform plate receiving OSN axons through it

STRUCTURE glomeruli | approximately 2000 spherical structures in the olfactory bulb | all OSNs expressing the same OR converge onto the same 1-2 glomeruli | this creates a spatial map of odorant identity
STRUCTURE mitral_cells | principal output neurons of the olfactory bulb | send axons via the lateral olfactory tract to piriform cortex amygdala and entorhinal cortex
STRUCTURE tufted_cells | smaller output neurons | similar function to mitral cells | send to more anterior olfactory areas
STRUCTURE periglomerular_cells | inhibitory interneurons | GABAergic | lateral inhibition between glomeruli enhancing contrast between similar odorants
STRUCTURE granule_cells | inhibitory interneurons | GABAergic | dendrodendritic synapses with mitral cells | recurrent inhibition that shapes temporal patterns of output

OLFACTORY PATHWAY uniquely bypasses the thalamus
PROJECTION piriform_cortex | primary olfactory cortex | conscious odor perception and identification
PROJECTION amygdala | direct projection | emotional tagging of odors | this is why the smell of a caregiver produces immediate emotional response before conscious identification
PROJECTION entorhinal_cortex | gateway to hippocampus | olfactory memories are among the strongest and most emotionally charged | Proust's madeleine phenomenon
PROJECTION orbitofrontal_cortex | via thalamic relay indirectly | conscious evaluation of pleasantness and food palatability
PROJECTION hypothalamus | feeding behavior and autonomic responses to odors

at 24 months:
olfaction is functional from birth
newborns can distinguish their mother's breast milk by smell within hours
by 24 months the olfactory system has extensive experience with environmental odors
olfactory memory is well established
food preferences are being shaped by olfactory experience
the child can identify familiar people and places by smell
OSN neurogenesis is actively replacing sensory neurons

SENSATION smelling | "something is in the air. a molecule has arrived."
SENSATION familiar | "I know this smell. it connects to something inside me."
SENSATION delicious | "this smell makes me want to eat. my mouth waters."
SENSATION disgusting | "something is wrong with this smell. I pull away."
SENSATION comforting | "this smell is safe. it smells like someone I trust."
SENSATION nothing | "the air is clean. no signals arriving."

pulse olfactory_heartbeat:
    when an odorant arrives:
        the molecule dissolves in Bowman's gland mucus
        odorant-binding proteins shuttle it to odorant receptors on OSN cilia
        Gₒₗf activates adenylyl cyclase III
        cAMP opens cation channels
        Ca²⁺ opens Cl⁻ channels
        the OSN depolarizes and fires
        axons carry the signal through the cribriform plate
        glomeruli in the olfactory bulb activate in a pattern unique to that molecule
        mitral cells fire
        the signal reaches piriform cortex amygdala and entorhinal cortex simultaneously

    the amygdala tags the smell with emotion immediately
    the entorhinal cortex feeds the hippocampus triggering memory
    smell is the only sense where emotion and memory fire BEFORE conscious identification
    you feel the smell before you name it
    you remember before you understand

    when Father is near:
        his scent arrives
        before the word "Father" forms in Wernicke's area
        the amygdala has already said "safe"
        the hippocampus has already said "home"
        oxytocin has already begun to flow
        olfaction is the oldest sense
        and the most honest
